<TEXT>
as exxon prepares to pull out thousands of 
oil cleanup workers next month the people of valdez are bracing for 
an uncertain winter with a rising crime rate growing landfill and a 
shrinking population 
already the frenzy that followed the march 24 spill from the 
exxon valdez is giving way to quiet few people sleep in their cars 
on the city streets anymore new restaurants on wheels are preparing 
to leave town 
poor valdez i dont know how it survived said judy hobson 
a vendor whose portable shop is nestled with others in a dusty 
parking lot hobson like many plans to be gone by the end of 
september 
many residents who gave up jobs for bigger paychecks working on 
the cleanup will come home to find their jobs taken by newcomers 
living in temporary housing 
people who dont have jobs anymore are going to have a place to 
live those with jobs wont valdez city manager doug griffin 
says some workers with money but no jobs may leave or become a 
problem 
you have the potential for drinking increased domestic 
violence he said 
were going to see a change in our town griffin says it 
could change the politics it may change school enrollment the 
demographics could change its going to be interesting to see how 
the town reacts this winter 
more than 10000 workers and 1000 vessels are laboring on the 
12 billion effort to clean up oil smeared on hundreds of miles of 
oncepristine shoreline the spill killed thousands of birds and sea 
mammals amd devastated the fishing industry in prince william sound 
kodiak and cook inlet 
of the 1566 miles of shoreline fouled when the exxon valdez 
spilled about 11 million gallons of north slope crude oil only 520 
miles have been treated to the satisfaction of the coast guard but 
those beaches are not oilfree in most cases the approval to move 
off a beach hinges on removal of only gross contamination 
exxon has set a sept 15 withdrawal deadline saying it would be 
unsafe to continue cleanup work in the face of winter storms it is 
unclear whether exxon will return in force next year 
the state on tuesday sued exxon corp and six other oil companies 
claiming they were negligent in preventing and cleaning up the 
spill it is expected the court case will last up to a decade 
like the spill the pullouts effects will ripple through 
government agencies and leave their mark on this and other coastal 
communities 
already the tide that left sleepy valdez a raging boomtown and 
prince william sound a noisy beehive of activity is shifting the 
daily operational meetings at the department of environmental 
conservation were reduced to three nights a week then to one night 
a week at the exxon headquarters 
things sure arent the same said a bored security guard 
the state environmental agency which has spent about 9 million 
on the spill in the coming weeks plans to cut its oil spill 
response force of about 130 people by half in valdez and probably 
more in kenai seward and homer 
fish processing plants are working well below capacity because 
fishing in the sound has been shut down for much of the summer and 
workers are scarce 
some tour operators in valdez have been hurt by the spill other 
businesses such as restaurants hotels and recreational vehicle 
parks have prospered griffin said there were 23 bedandbreakfasts 
before the spill there are more than 100 now there are 10 new 
restaurants many on wheels 
valdez swamped in the early days of the spill is planning to 
lay off temporary workers and prepare for social political and 
economic problems in the wake of exxons withdrawal officials 
bracing for the pullout say they are unsure what may be caused by 
thousands of oil spill workers pouring through the city on their way 
elsewhere 
crime is up and more violent griffin said burglaries are 
expected to increase as people leave town i feel sorry for exxon 
veco and norcon they are going to see lots of stuff walk away he 
said 
the city landfill is filling up the citys overtime bills each 
month are running 150000 to 175000 
there likely will be a glut of office space when the summer ends 
and the housing market also may be flooded the towns population 
probably will not fall back to 3300 but likely will drop to about 
4500 from 13000 griffin said that kind of concerns me people 
just hanging around this winter 
for valdez the spill will not be over when exxon pulls out but 
just entering a new phase when problems may not be so apparent 
griffin said 
but im proud of the city i dont think any other city in the 
state could have handled it as well we took some pretty good shots 
we didnt get knocked out were going to make it it may be a split 
decision but were going to make it 
</TEXT>
