<TEXT>
hooves thunder and swords flash as 
warriors on horseback battle hordes of infidels a leopard stalks a 
bear dances and a princess in white chiffon smiles radiantly at the 
assembled masses 
the famed moscow circus is getting its best acts together and 
taking them on the road this year the road is winding through the 
united states and canada for only the second time in the past decade 
among those taking part is showman tamerlane nugzarov leader of 
the famous troupe of horsemen who perform the theatrical 
eyepopping acrobatics that are among the bestknown features of the 
storied circus 
but while nugzarov is one of the soviet unions great showmen he 
would not be embarking on a ninemonth north america tour if not for 
the promotional abilities of an even flashier figure president 
mikhail s gorbachev 
hes the best promotion man whos ever left the soviet union 
said steve leber a new york promoter who says he is putting up more 
than 15 million to finance the tour he has singlehandedly made 
the american public curious about the soviet union 
leber and the circus first capitalized on the wests fascination 
with all things soviet last year when the circus toured the united 
states for the first time in 10 years 
this year the circus and leber have signed an agreement to keep 
the circus returning yearly circus authorities pay the performers 
regular salaries and leber covers north american expenses 
hopefully well gross four times that leber said of his 
investment 
he said the deal guarantees the circus against loss and gives it 
more than half the profits 
this years road show goes beyond the regular moscow circus 
leber said it is among the best of 1400 circus acts nationwide the 
troupe recently completed a onemonth dress rehearsal in leningrad 
and opens its north american tour in toronto on wednesday night 
among the acts is bear trainer raisa ibragimovish who shares a 
first name and a strong resemblance with the soviet unions first 
lady 
the show also features an acrobat who looks like actor michael j 
fox haunting russian folk songs and soviet and us flags that 
seem to appear when the lush music hits its most grandiose peaks 
despite the goodwill there often are snags when western business 
interests hatch deals with communist countries 
look what happened in china said leber its 
nervewracking 
the moscow circus in fact almost remained stuck in its 
namesake on the day that animals and equipment were to be loaded 
onto a freighter for the voyage to canada the culture ministry 
denied the circus a license to export the show 
one of the underlings in the ministry of culture said your 
contract is too long and too good were holding up the ship 
leber said 
even a few days delay would have jeopardized wednesday nights 
opening at the canadian national exhibition in toronto leber said 
i had the blessing of the circus and i thought they had 
control of their own destiny with this new freedom of gorbachevs 
reforms but the ministry of culture still had that one power and 
with it they could really mess you up this is no way to do 
business 
a day later after leber cut the length of the contract from five 
years to one the ministry relented 
when ministry officials were asked what happened spokesman 
vladimir benyukh replied that is an internal affair and they do 
not have to divulge the secrets 
culture minister vasily zakharov apparently was not involved he 
had lost his job days earlier when the newly powerful soviet 
parliament rejected him in the countrys first cabinet confirmation 
hearings the culture ministry has long been a source of shame for 
progressive soviets since it was responsible for repressing 
artists theater directors and writers who didnt toe the communist 
party line 
if anything the soviets involved in the circus are learning a 
little about westernstyle promotion 
meanwhile his general manager ted thrasher is offering much 
gentler lessons to the circus people about the harsh reality of 
competition in the western world 
late in the evening after one of the last rehearsals in 
leningrad tour general manager ted thrasher and leber dined with 
nugzarov and some other soviets someone reveling in the spirit of 
sovietamerican goodwill offered a toast to christopher columbus 
the discoverer of america 
well we can toast him thrasher allowed but this is a 
very important lesson christopher columbus was not the first but 
he had the best publicity 
