refugees were entering ethiopia daily up from 150 at the beginning 
of august 
the refugees had reported heavy fighting between the rebel somali 
national movement and government troops around the garrison town of 
borama near the ethiopian border peters said 
borama is about 60 miles northwest of hargeisa somalias 
secondlargest town 
the refugees mostly women and children are camped in a remote 
area six miles from the border and about 250 miles northeast of 
ethiopias capital addis ababa 
peters who returned from a visit to the area wednesday said the 
un agency would start caring for the refugees as soon as ethiopian 
authorities moved them to more easily accessible areas farther 
inside the country 
they are the latest in a wave of refugees who started coming 
across the border in may 1988 when fighting intensified between the 
rebels and government troops around the northern towns of hargeisa 
burao and berbera an estimated 350000 somalis have sought refuge 
in unmanaged camps near jijiga about 60 miles southwest of the 
new arrivals 
the somali national movement has been fighting to topple the 
government of president mohamed siad barre since 1981 
exiled dissidents recently have claimed barres government has 
lost control of all but the capital and is experiencing the most 
widespread fighting across the east african nation since barre 
seized power in 1969 
