<TEXT>
president wojciech jaruzelski will choose a 
solidarity member to lead polands next government a lawmaker said 
thursday a move that would end four decades of communist domination 
the stunning development came during a historic meeting between 
jaruzelski and lech walesa whose solidarity labor movement was 
crushed by jaruzelski eight years ago but which has now become 
polands most potent political force 
solidarity lawmaker jacek kuron said jaruzelski accepted in 
principle walesas offer to form a government led by 
noncommunists such a government would be unprecedented in the 
soviet bloc 
i am satisfied walesa said after the meeting 
even in a government led by solidarity however jaruzelski would 
remain president controlling the army and foreign affairs local 
governments would still be in the hands of the communist party and 
party members would still control the courts in addition tens of 
thousands of polands bureaucrats owe their jobs to the party and 
75 percent of management jobs ranging from shop managers to 
factory heads are held by party members 
the possibility of a noncommunist government in warsaw has 
alarmed the soviet union polands superpower neighbor and ally but 
the soviets have always stressed that political changes in poland 
were an internal affair in addition walesa has said that the 
interior and defense ministries would remain in communist hands 
after the meeting between walesa and jaruzelski staterun media 
announced that communist prime minister czeslaw kiszczak formally 
turned in his resignation to jaruzelski apparently as a prelude to 
the formation of a new government 
kiszczak who has been in office only since aug 2 had said 
earlier this week he would resign because the solidarityled 
opposition in parliament fought his efforts to form a coalition 
government 
walesa a gdansk shipyard electrician who built his labor 
movement as poland slid into an economic morass has said he does 
not want to become prime minister 
jaruzelski as president must nominate a prime minister and 
present him for approval to the sejm the lower house of the 
national assembly solidarity and two minor parties that are allied 
with it form a majority in that chamber 
kuron said he is among three solidarity candidates the coalition 
has offered for prime minister kuron a activist in the polish 
opposition for more than 20 years spent nine years in prison for 
antigovernment activities 
