<TEXT>
the massachusetts port authority unreasonably and 
illegally imposed a dual set of landing fees to discourage small 
planes from using logan international airport a federal appeals 
court ruled thursday 
a threejudge panel of the 1st us circuit court of appeals 
wrote that massports its landing fee system had been 
unscientifically developed and unfairly discriminated against small 
planes 
massports policy was based on the premise that commercial jets 
carrying 400 passengers should have priority over a sixseat private 
plane but federal law has long held that all aircraft should have 
equal access to us runways 
the us department of transportation which objected to 
massports fees has broad authority and responsibility to 
regulate navigable airspace to assure its efficient use and to 
protect the right of freedom of transit through navigable 
airspace the court ruled 
massport officials said they were disapppointed with the decision 
but hope to work with new leadership at the transportation 
department in washington to ease delay and congestion at logan 
massport last year raised the landing fee for small aircraft at 
logan from a flat 25 per touchdown to a minimum of 100 at the 
same time commercial jet fees were cut a jumbo jet for example 
saw its 800 fee cut in half 
the owners of private and commuter planes complained but traffic 
dropped by onethird and ontime performance for commercial jets 
surged from last place among the countrys 27 largest airports in 
may 1988 to second place in december 1988 
