crawled under the house and caught small animals for food 
the homeowners had been calling people for a month but no one 
wanted to go after it said hardwick whose company traps nuisance 
animals in south florida people say theyve seen it eat 30pound 
raccoons like they were marshmallows 
hardwick believes the snake is the largest ever captured in south 
florida where many exotic pets are illegally released into the wild 
the reticulate python a native of southeastern asia and 
indonesia can grow to more than 30 feet the snakes which are not 
venomous coil around their prey to stop breathing and blood flow 
on wednesday hardwick and a crew began digging tunnels below the 
home they found the snake about eight feet underground next to a 
concrete wall 
hardwick said he hooked the snake around the head with a pole 
snare he and his helpers then wrestled it down and yanked it out of 
the tunnel 
it was like it was daring us to challenge him said hardwick 
he said he hopes to sell the snake to a zoo or serpentarium 
</TEXT>
