<DOCNO> AP890817-0189 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
amid an unfolding criminal investigation of dozens 
of futures traders the nations two leading exchanges are 
developing an electronic watchdog to make sure trading pits are on 
the upandup 
if the system works as planned floor traders will graduate from 
the pencilandpad era of recording hundreds of millions of trades 
annually 
the idea is to close a gap that gives unscrupulous traders room 
to manipulate their deals without a precise record of what theyve 
done 
under the system being developed by the chicago board of trade 
and the chicago mercantile exchange traders will record their deals 
immediately using handheld devices that transmit the data into the 
exchange computers 
these instruments will not have an eraser on one end merc 
executive leo melamed said wednesday 
among the 46 indicted traders at the two exchanges some were 
accused of simply changing prices on their penciledin records when 
it would mean a profit for themselves or confederates 
melamed said the new system would provide an audit trail that 
could prevent most if not all of the indictable offenses the 
government identified in its 2year undercover investigation 
the improved audit trail system said merc spokesman andrew 
yemma would give an almost instantaneous recording of all the 
pertinent data of a trade the price the trading partner the 
commodity and the time of the transaction 
under the present system floor traders record their trades by 
writing on cards which are picked up at the pits by clerks every 30 
minutes or so 
in 85 percent of the trades the time of the transaction is 
correct to within a minute said yemma but even as short a time as 
a minute can give an unscrupulous trader plenty of opportunity for 
manipulation 
for example a trader who has an extra large purchase order from 
a customer could buy the commodity for his own account first then 
execute the customers order the trader would profit from the jump 
in price triggered by his customers large buy order 
the merc and the board of trade each contributed 25 million 
toward the development for the handheld units and invited other 
us futures exchanges to join in the effort 
while the exchanges were announcing their plans a yen trader at 
the merc entered an innocent plea to charges of racketeering 
conspiracy fraud and violations of the commodities act 
james m marren 39 became the 14th trader to plead innocent 
no trial date has been set for any of the accused and defense 
attorneys told us district judge george marovich on wednesday they 
