<TEXT>
mississippis top economic development 
official says the state has two images in corporate america bad 
and none at all and hopes to correct that with a new national 
advertising campaign 
the first of the ads which describe mississippi as the state 
of change appeared thursday in the eastern and chicago editions 
of the wall street journal 
were trying to make a subtle change in the image of 
mississippi j mac holladay director of the state department of 
economic and community development said wednesday at a news 
conference were trying to get corporate america to look at 
mississippi in a different way 
the states history of civil rights conflicts its high 
illiteracy rate and its low average income levels have created a bad 
image for the state in some quarters holladay has argued that past 
image campaigns have failed to reach the right audience and left 
many people with no image of the state at all 
the fullpage ad carries a quote from 19thcentury british poet 
alfred lord tennyson a photograph of a space shuttle launch and 
copy which points out mississippis links to the us space program 
the national aeronautics and space administration test facility 
in south mississippi has grown over the past 28 years into the 
13480acre stennis space center which houses a space shuttle 
engine testing laboratory and scientific think tank employing more 
than 5500 workers the ad said 
it also notes that nasa earlier this year decided to build a 
solid rocket motor assembly plant in northeast missisippi 
the wall street journals eastern edition is distributed to east 
coast states from maine to florida and in west virginia georgia 
alabama and tennessee the chicago edition reaches metropolitan 
chicago gary ind and milwaukee 
a color version of the ad will appear in forbes business week 
and industry week magazines the department placed 17 ads in the 
wall street journal 10 in business week nine in forbes and five in 
industry week 
additional ads are being developed holladay said 
the second ad will focus on the states workforce with a photo of 
the march 8 edition of national geographic magazine as the 
centerpiece the magazine is printed in corinth 
the third ad planned for this spring is to focus on a new 
education reform package on which gov ray mabus and his staff are 
working holladay said if the legislature does not approve the 
governors program weve got a lot of strong things to put in 
there 
the ads were developed by department staffers at a cost of less 
than 30000 godwin group a jackson advertising agency helped 
with copywriting and some photography holladay said 
he said the department placed its own ads and has spent about 
818550 on the campaign 
the state legislature in its 1989 session appropriated 2 million 
to the department with the amount to be divided equally among 
corporate and tourism advertising programs 
holladay said the ninemonth program that begins with the wall 
street journal ads was just a beginning 
we cant do this just one year and stop the next year he 
said 
holladay said he would ask the 1990 legislature to double the 
departments advertising budget 
