<TEXT>
ian posgate a former star insurance underwriter 
with lloyds of london was acquitted thursday of conspiracy to steal 
60 million of insurance funds to buy a personal stake in a swiss 
bank 
the case had threatened lloyds 300yearold reputation for 
reliability when it broke in 1982 
posgate 57 was called goldfinger at the height of his 
success for his midas touch in the city of london financial 
district he took high risks in undercutting premiums to become the 
worlds single largest insurer of shipping with 25 percent of the 
market 
i can only say that i feel totally vindicated after seven very 
long years posgate said thursday after the 15week trial at 
southwark crown court in london 
he said he would not return to lloyds 
posgate had managed lloyds underwriting syndicates controlled by 
the brokerage firm alexander howden posgates codefendant former 
howden chairman kenneth grob 68 also was cleared of theft charges 
the verdict came after three days of deliberations by the jury of 
seven men and five women 
prosecutor michael hill alleged that posgate was lured into a 
plot masterminded by grob that siphoned off millions of dollars from 
their syndicates into secret offshore holdings in panama 
hill said the money was moved to lichtenstein to purchase the 
banque du rhone et de la tamise in geneva 
grob resigned immediately after howdens was taken over in 
january 1982 by the us insurance company alexander and alexander 
services inc for 255 million 
posgate said he was taking part in legitimate insurance dealing 
and grob said contracts signed were legitimate reinsurance to the 
benefit of howdens and he never spent any of the money 
posgate was cleared by a lloyds disciplinary committee in 1984 
which found he was not involved in an agreement to use money taken 
from his syndicate to buy the bank but he was arrested on similar 
charges in 1987 
